al_normalized": true, "mention": "M1 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9834160804748535, "span": {"begin": 625, "end": 637}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:39462"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "pilocarpine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9973680377006531, "span": {"begin": 660, "end": 671}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rat", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9348485469818115, "span": {"begin": 720, "end": 723}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:48882"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atropine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.5639219284057617, "span": {"begin": 749, "end": 757}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:841"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mAChR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9885593056678772, "span": {"begin": 761, "end": 766}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019954"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "cholinergic symptoms", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8427010178565979, "span": {"begin": 799, "end": 819}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012640"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "convulsions", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9976546764373779, "span": {"begin": 828, "end": 839}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010830"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "physostigmine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9929836988449097, "span": {"begin": 886, "end": 899}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:43"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AChE", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9584253430366516, "span": {"begin": 914, "end": 918}}], "text": "Investigations into receptors involved in cholinergic seizures have found that pre-treatment with the selective M1 antagonist pirenzepine abolished seizures in 91% of the rats tested. The drugs mecamylamine, a nicotinic antagonist, and methoctramine, a M1 receptor antagonist, did not significantly affect seizure activity (Cruickshank et al., 1994).  Muscarinic antagonists were effective in lessening the seizure activity in guinea pig hippocampal slices (Harrison et al., 2004).  M1- deficient mice neurons lacked the modulation of M-current caused by muscarinic agonists that is shown in wild-type mice. The mice lacking M1 receptors are also resistant to pilocarpine-induced seizures (Hamilton et al., 1997).  In a rat study, pretreatment with atropine, a mAChR antagonist, was able to prevent cholinergic symptoms such as convulsions and acute mortality following an injection of physostigmine, a reversible AChE inhibitor (Davis and Hatoum, 1980).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:15:26 +0000 2026"}